    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. is there a specific downside to using that greedy method for longer routes though? like, when does the logic start falling apart or getting really inefficient?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The nearest-neighbor method can perform poorly over longer routes or complex road networks because it never looks ahead to see if taking a slightly longer path now would save significant distance later. For example, if it skips a nearby hub to grab a closer one, it might end up with a long detour later that the other nodes could have been served more efficiently with. This local greediness often results in a solution that is \"good enough\" quickly but missing the global optimum, especially in scenarios with tight time windows or congested traffic where the straight-line distance isn't a perfect proxy for travel time.",
      "source": "target",
